com.bluegosling.collections

Class CollectionUtils

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.bluegosling.collections.CollectionUtils

  • public final class CollectionUtils
extends Object
    Utility functions for implementing standard collection interfaces. Some of the functionality in this class overlaps with implementations in AbstractCollection and its abstract sub-classes. These methods are useful for situations where extending one of those classes is not suitable.

      • naturalOrder

        public static Comparator<Object> naturalOrder()
        Exactly the same as Comparator.naturalOrder(), but can be used to compare objects whose type is unknown. The comparator will throw a ClassCastException if presented with arguments that aren't mutually comparable.

      • toString

        public static String toString(Iterable<?> coll)
        Constructs a string representation of the specified collection.

        Empty collections are represented as "[ ]". A collection with a single element would be represented as "[ item ]", where "item" is the value of String.valueOf(theOneItem). Collections with multiple items follow the same pattern, with multiple items separated by a comma and a single space, like so: "[ item1, item2, item3 ]".

        Parameters:
        coll - the collection
        Returns:
        a string representation of coll

      • filter

        public static boolean filter(Collection<?> items,
                             Iterator<?> iter,
                             boolean remove)
        Filters all objects in the list against a specified collection. Either removes all items that are found in specified collection or removes all items that are not found in the collection. Uses Iterator.remove() to remove items from the target list.
        Parameters:
        items - collection of items acting as a filter
        iter - iterator over the target collection, from which items will be removed
        remove - true if removing all items found in the collection or false if retaining them
        Returns:
        true if the list was modified and something was removed

      • removeAll

        public static boolean removeAll(Collection<?> collection,
                                Iterator<?> itemsToRemove)
        Removes from a collection all items retrieved from a specified iterator. This can be used to implement Collection.removeAll(Collection) for a collection that has a fast (e.g. logarithmic or constant time) remove operation. For collections with slower (e.g. linear) remove operations, filter(Collection, Iterator, boolean) will be the better choice.

        Examples:

         // Using CollectionUtils.removeAll()
  @Override public boolean removeAll(Collection<?> c) {
   return CollectionUtils.removeAll(this, c.iterator());
 } 
 
 // Alternate implementation instead using CollectionUtils.filter()
  @Override public boolean removeAll(Collection<?> c) {
   return CollectionUtils.filter(c, iterator(), true);
 }
        Parameters:
        collection - the collection from which items are to be removed
        itemsToRemove - the items to remove
        Returns:
        true if the collection was modified (e.g. one or more items actually removed)

      • removeAll

        public static boolean removeAll(Set<?> collection,
                                Iterator<?> itemsToRemove)
        Removes from a set all items retrieved from a specified iterator.

        The only difference between this method and removeAll(Collection, Iterator) is that this version assumes the collection cannot have duplicates (after all, it is a set). So it invokes Set.remove(Object) only once per item to remove. Since other collections may have duplicates, the other version must invoke the method until it returns false (indicating that no more occurrences are in the collection).

        Parameters:
        collection - the collection from which items are to be removed
        itemsToRemove - the items to remove
        Returns:
        true if the collection was modified (e.g. one or more items actually removed)
        See Also:
        removeAll(Collection, Iterator)

      • isInRangeLow

        public static <T> boolean isInRangeLow(T o,
                                       boolean oIncluded,
                                       T from,
                                       boolean fromInclusive,
                                       Comparator<? super T> comp)
        Checks if the given object (or range lower bound) lies above another lower bound.

        Generally, this is used to test if an object is above the specified lower bound (in which case, the parameter oIncluded will be true). But we can also tell if the lower bound of one range (specified by the parameters o and oIncluded) lies above the lower bound of another range (specified by from and fromInclusive).

        Type Parameters:
        T - the type of the element
        Parameters:
        o - the object
        oIncluded - true if o needs to be included in the range
        from - the lower bound of the range
        fromInclusive - true if from is included in the range; false otherwise
        comp - the comparator used to compare o to from (cannot be null)
        Returns:
        true if the specified object is greater than the bound and the bound is exclusive; true if the object is greater than or equal to the bound and the bound is inclusive; false otherwise

      • isInRangeHigh

        public static <T> boolean isInRangeHigh(T o,
                                        boolean oIncluded,
                                        T to,
                                        boolean toInclusive,
                                        Comparator<? super T> comp)
        Checks if the given object (or range upper bound) falls under another upper bound.

        Generally, this is used to test if an object is under the specified upper bound (in which case, the parameter oIncluded will be true). But we can also tell if the upper bound of one range (specified by the parameters o and oIncluded) falls under the upper bound of another range (specified by to and toInclusive).

        Type Parameters:
        T - the type of the element
        Parameters:
        o - the object
        oIncluded - true if o needs to be included in the range
        to - the upper bound of the range
        toInclusive - true if to is included in the range, false otherwise
        comp - the comparator used to compare o to to (cannot be null)
        Returns:
        true if the specified object is less than the bound and the bound is exclusive, true if the object is less than or equal to the bound and the bound is inclusive, and false otherwise

      • removeObject

        public static boolean removeObject(Object item,
                                   Iterator<?> iter,
                                   boolean justFirst)
        Removes a specified object using an iterator. This helper method implements remove(Object), removeAll(Collection<?>), removeFirstOccurrence(Object), and even {code removeLastOccurrence(Object)} (the lattermost of which uses a MoreIterators.reverseListIterator(ListIterator) to find the last occurrence instead of the first).
        Parameters:
        item - the item to remove
        iter - the iterator from which to remove the item
        justFirst - true if just removing the first matching item or false if removing all matching items
        Returns:
        true if the item was found and removed or false if the item was not found in the iterator
